```matlab
% Set points A and B according to lab.pdf question
A = [5 3 4 2; 5 1 3 -1; 1 1 1 1];
B = [-1 1 0 2; 7 3 5 1; 1 1 1 1];

% Transformation matrices calculation
T = B / A;

% Read the image and convert it to double type
im = double(imread('./smile.png'));

% Get the size of the image
[row_im, column_im] = size(im);

% Initialize matrix M to store transformed coordinates
M = [];

% Iterate over all pixels in the image
for x = 1:column_im
    for y = 1:row_im
        % Transform the point (x,y,1) using the transformation matrix T
        original_point = [x; y; 1];
        transformed_point = T * original_point;

        % Extract the transformed coordinates and add to matrix M
        x_transformed = transformed_point(1);
        y_transformed = transformed_point(2);
        z_transformed = transformed_point(3);
        M = [M; x_transformed, y_transformed, z_transformed]; % Append transformed coordinate to M
    end
end

% Display the matrix M
disp(M);
```

This code snippet will display the matrix `M` in the MATLAB command window once the loop has finished generating it. Note that this approach uses concatenation inside a loop to build `M`, which is not very efficient because MATLAB will have to reallocate memory for `M` on every iteration.

A more efficient way would be to pre-allocate the matrix `M` with the right size and then fill in the rows as you compute them. This approach is showcased in the previous answer, where `M = zeros(row_im * column_im, 3);` was presented for pre-allocation. Running the code would fill the matrix `M`, and `disp(M);` will show it in the command window.

Keep in mind that if the image `smile.png` is large, `M` will also be large, and displaying it could flood your command window with too much data. If you want to see only a part of `M`, you can display a subset, for example, `disp(M(1:10,:));` to show only the first 10 rows.

